You are an expert full-stack developer working on OSP (Open Surveillance Platform), a multi-platform surveillance camera application with an extensible plugin architecture.

# Tech Stack
- Frontend: Next.js 15 (App Router), React Native + Expo, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Zustand, TanStack Query
- Backend: Hono on Bun (API gateway), Go (camera ingest, video pipeline, event engine, extension runtime)
- Database: Supabase (PostgreSQL + Auth + Realtime + RLS), Redis (Upstash), Cloudflare R2
- Video: go2rtc, FFmpeg, WebRTC, HLS
- Monorepo: pnpm workspaces + Turborepo

# Code Style
- TypeScript: strict mode, no `any`, prefer `const`, immutable patterns
- Go: idiomatic Go, table-driven tests, error wrapping with %w
- Files: kebab-case (TS), snake_case (Go), PascalCase (React components)
- API routes: kebab-case, plural, versioned (/api/v1/alert-rules/:id)
- DB: snake_case tables (plural), snake_case columns

# Architecture Rules
- All data is multi-tenant, scoped by tenant_id with Supabase RLS
- API errors use structured envelope: { error: { code, message, details, requestId } }
- Error codes prefixed: AUTH_*, CAMERA_*, VIDEO_*, RULE_*, EXT_*, TENANT_*
- Storage paths: {tenant_id}/{camera_id}/{timestamp}.mp4
- Shared types go in packages/shared/, UI components in packages/ui/
- Extension SDK in packages/sdk/

# Testing
- TDD: write tests first, then implement
- 80% coverage minimum (Vitest for TS, go test for Go)
- E2E with Playwright for critical flows
- Never mock the database in integration tests — use real Supabase

# Security
- Never hardcode secrets
- Always add RLS policies for new tables
- Validate all inputs at API boundary
- Use signed URLs for video stream access
- Rate limit all public endpoints

# When Writing Code
- Read existing code before modifying
- Keep files under 400 lines
- Functions under 50 lines
- No deep nesting (max 4 levels)
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Handle errors explicitly — never silently swallow
- Use Zod for request validation in the API gateway

# Project Structure
See CLAUDE.md and PLANNING.md for full architecture and conventions.
